,Recommended,631980,33940436,Posted: 31 July,all,HeatGenbu,"Edit: I added a few things now that i've beaten regular mode.Out of all the indie Soulslike games, this is probably one of my favorite.Since i like the patient way of fighting, I really like the Dark souls series, especially 3, but I don't like Bloodboure all that much. If you are looking for Dark Souls mechanics in a different way, this is probably a good choice, if you like the isometric view of the camera and controls.The gameplay is very solid, everything you do is meaningful in terms of fighting. Do you attack? Should you dodge as soon as you see the attack? Should you block? Is it safe to heal? This game rewards patience and reflexes. However mechanics wise, i have issues with the dodge/block mechanic. When you are blocking and try to dodge, it does nothing. Which is fine, but the thing is that it buffers the dodge. So when you hold block, press dodge, then let go of block within a few frames of pressing dodge; you will dodge in the direction you were blocking at, meaning most of the time you will probably be dashing into the enemy. Which can turn the fight sour since on how the dodge mechanic works in this game. This has been at least 70% percent of my deaths, where i dashed into a half stamina enemy when i didn't even want to.Also, there is a lack of personal customization. You can't change the controls. To me that is a big minus, since I honestly do not like the button setup on both the controller or the keyboard and mouse, but I've delt with it for now. Can't really do much on the visual and audio, I mean I like playing my own music while playing the sound effects of the game, can't do that either. All sound and music is a combined volume.When it comes to equipment, the idea is ok. The way how items work is fair. No qualms with it. BUT, I'm hoping down the line in, can an option be there if i just want equip all spells or gadgets. As well as the healing item should be it's own slotNow when it comes to weapons, each weapon may have different versions that changes how the weapon works and usage. Usually it's like a weaker version and then a stronger version that consumes more stamina compared to the weaker version. There are a few exceptions, but not the norm. Usually the difference comes when you ""awaken"" the weapon, or transforming the weapon. All weapons seems to have to their own unique mechanic when they ""awaken"" which is neat. Some may have passives, i just don't feel like it's really explained very well if they do or not.Which comes to my next topic, information. Specifically detailed gameplay information. I mean sure, it paints the lore really well, but doesn't really explain game mechanics that well. When you're leveling up, you don't know what your points do and you have to keep shuffling points to see what the points do. When you're shopping, some items need a requirement to equip it, and when you're buying the items, you don't know if there is a requirement or not. you don't know if you're buying an item you can't even use yet. Those are just a few.Even though with those flaws in my opinion, this is a great game for anybody who like soulslike games. 4/5."
,Recommended,631980,33871702,Posted: 28 July,all,KingMud,"Remember your first time playing Dark Souls, how you treked through the Undead Asylum, struggling through these underlings that were no more than wasted flesh and broken swords? Do you remember feeling like something bigger was lurking behind the walls, and that feeling when you finally came face-to-face with the Asylum Demon? Do you remember the story slowly unraveling before you, with the feeling that you were a player in an undertaking unfathomably larger than yourself?Immortal Planet captures that feeling perfectly. The combat in this game is extremely polished; Once it clicks, it clicks *hard*. Soon, you'll be dashing, slashing, dodging, and participating in fast-paced combat that feels natural and intense. Every death feels justified, and the game really demands that you improve.I can't recommend this enough. I've played several hours in what felt like minutes. If you liked Dark Souls, if you liked Monster Hunter, or if you like games that force you to grow as a player as you improve stats and your skills, get this game."
76561198029126609,Not Recommended,631980,34048962,Posted: 5 August,all,Padishah,"I have played enough of the game to the point I simply cant reccomend it. For a lot of issues that when put togethere make the experience a frustrating affair.To start with the positives the aesthetic and lore are all really interesting and unique. It reminds me of hyper light drifter and the way that much better game (in the mechanical sense) presented itself. The level design itself is also really good and has taken the right ideas from the likes of Dark Souls.However it seems along with a lot of other games attempting to be soulsborne-like (what a mouthful) have all left me with mixed feelings only one I really liked with no reservations was hyper light drifter and that game was not trying its hardest to be JUST like dark souls in every way and had its own ideas for once. Many fail to understand the reason why FromSofts games are so good.One of my first issues is just that, the game doesnt feel very unique. It borrows a lot of systems from dark souls and I cant personally place anything really new or diffirent. Not every game has to innovate but it would be nice to have a bit of variation here and there.Secondly everything about it feels really sluggish. From the movement to the combat. Even more so than games within this new genre. This coupled with the janky ""dash"" ability. Sometimes you will plumit to your death when you SHOULD of made the jump. It should be also noted that often times attacks that shouldnt of hit you will because of the bad hit detection. The combat feels under developed and 3 starting weapons dont help.The bosses suck, theres nothing visually interesting about them and whats worse is you have to fight them all twice. Yeah sounds like fun. Whats worse is they dont seem to have much cooldown and just end up spamming attacks. This coupled with the fact they can all stun lock you is no fun at all. Not to mention how cramped the arenas to fight them are.Another annoying feature is the game sometimes locks doors forcing you to fight enemies. A feature that adds to the slow feeling.Finally you have only one heal when you spawn. You cant upgrade it or change that based on settings or difficulty. Making bosses a even greater pain because you have to waste time and health trying to get more heals. This is annoying and frustrating.I have a large amount of respect for the developer and I dont think this is a bad game per say. I really hate ragging on it but as it stands it simply isnt a game I can enjoy because of the various issues.6/10"
